    <text>
        <body>
            <div xml:id="d.1">
                <head type="title">Miklós Oláh to Elek Thurzó (Brussels, 18 February 1532)</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p xml:id="reg.p.1">He hears that the Hungarians want a third king, they do
                            not want to obey either King Ferdinand I or King John I, and they want
                            to accomplish all this by St. George’s day. This misfortune should end
                            at last, God will have mercy. Thurzó understands the situation better
                            than anyone; but Oláh wrote to him about it because he did not want to
                            go back on his promise.</p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb facs="https://www.eleveltar.hu/kereso-portlet/spring/digitalcontent/getcontent/preservica/633E1420-72AF-4E90-A29C-A99EAA97EA8C
                    "/>
                <p xml:id="p.1">Ad Turzonem.</p>
                <p xml:id="p.2">Miram omnino rem audio nostros Hungaros fractos tam diuturnis malis
                    ac calamitatibus, velleque tertium regem deligere, et nec
                        <persName>Ferdinando</persName> nostro, nec <persName>Ioanni</persName>
                    parere, constituisse autem ad eam rem perficiendam festum <persName>Beati
                        Georgii</persName><note xml:id="note.1">In Hungary, we celebrate this feast
                        on 24 instead of 23 April.</note>. Faxit Deus, ut iam tandem finis malorum
                    imponatur, et felicia consequantur tempora. Non est in Dei clementia <del
                        corresp="Olahus">sperandum</del><add corresp="Olahus" type="corr"
                        >desperandum</add>, puniat licet nos ad tempus pro nostris sceleribus et
                    omnibus modis vocet ad resipiscentiam. Tamen ad postremum nostri miserebitur, ut
                    enim est iustus, sic et pius et misericors. Non igitur deferet nos, modo spem
                    certam in eius locemus bonitate, et certa illi fidamus mente. Credo te magis
                    esse rerum nostrarum conscium, quam alium, propterea a te potius haec
                    intelligere debere, quam ego tibi declarare. Tamen nolui ego quoque deesse meo
                    officio, quod tibi sum pollicitus. Vale et me, ut soles, ama.</p>
                <p xml:id="p.3"><placeName>Bruxellae</placeName> XVIII. Februarii MDXXXII.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
